latestIgtvVideos.caption:
🌎 day feels reminds me of a Chipotle ad, keep reading & sound on…

The very beginning of my health journey coincided with this beautiful Chipotle “back to the start” ad from 10 years ago.

The short message is that the industrialization of our food system is destroying the quality of our food and our health.

Whether you are vegan or carnivore, we all agree factory farming and ultra processed food need to be cleaned up.

Seeing this video for the first time reshaped how I looked at food and inspired me to start a career at a big food company to make a difference.

After 6 years, it was clear I had to leave to create the change I wanted and thus Lovebird was born.

In retrospect, this video is even more interesting as Chipotle wiped this from their brand account bc their actual meat sourcing practices did not measure up to the ideal in this video.  They are trying their best but it’s hard for big brands to change.

New brands like @forceofnaturemeats and many others have stepped forward to promote regenerative agriculture which gives me hope.

We like to talk about the earth as some seperate entity but remember, we ARE nature.  The pollution of nature is the pollution of ourselves. 🌎 ✌️

latestPosts.caption:
🚨 BREAKING: Kellogg’s has finally conceded!

They just announced they’ll be removing synthetic dyes from products like Froot Loops and Apple Jacks by the end of 2027.

Our whole family stood outside their headquarters in Michigan last year, demanding this change with hundreds of other families. We never knew if they would listen.

After all the resistance… to see this come full circle is incredible.

One more food giant down. Let’s keep the momentum going. 💪

latestPosts.caption:
sometimes it can be this simple - all the other things definitely help and health is more dynamic than one single attribute but this is a good reminder. 🤍 

the harvard study of adult development started in 1938 and is still ongoing.

it showed people more socially connected to family, friends, and community were happier, healthier, and lived longer than any other variable such as diet, exercise, fame, wealth, career, smoking or drinking, and medical history + genetics.

What do you think?  Nestlé, Conagra, General Mills & Kraft Heinz are all committing to remove artificial food dyes from their U.S. products.

🗓️ Timeline Overview:

Nestlé: Phasing out synthetic dyes by mid‑2026 ￼

Conagra: Targeting dye‑free status in frozen foods by end‑2025, and in K‑12 school products by 2026–27; full U.S. phase‑out by end‑2027 ￼

General Mills: Removing dyes from cereals & school foods by summer 2026, with all retail products dye‑free by end‑2027 

Kraft Heinz: No new products with synthetic dyes after 2025, and removing dyes from existing products by end‑2027 ￼

✅ Why It Matters:

Linked to ADHD, behavioral issues, cancer risk

Europe banned them years ago; the U.S. is catching up with FDA & HHS pushing for a national dye phase‑out by end‑2026 ￼

latestPosts.caption:
what do you think?  almost unbelievable until you look at the scratches on the metal caps. 👀 

plus, the corked glass wine bottles were plastic free and when they added an air-blast step during bottling it reduced plastics by 70%.

the big difference is between glass and plastic for soda brands (50x more plastic in glass) but there is still a meaningful difference in water brands too (3x more plastic in glass).

admittedly, i’m surprised by this. your best bet seems to be RO filters for your tap water.

i may do my own testing for american brands to confirm but for now, im skipping the painted metal caps on glass bottles.

https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0889157525005344
